  <text xml:lang="ta" type="edition">
    <body>
      <div rend="parallel">
        <p xml:id="KT301-kilavi">varaiviṭai vaippa “āṟṟakiṟṟiyō” eṉṟa tōḻikkuk kiḻatti colliyatu. </p>
        <p xml:lang="en">Spoken by HER to the confidante who said “do you have
          the strength?”, when the time for marriage was fixed. </p>
      </div>

      <div rend="parallel">
        <lg xml:id="KT301">
          <l> muḻavumuta laraiya taṭavunilaip peṇṇaik</l>
          <l> koḻumaṭa liḻaitta ciṟukōṟ kuṭampaik</l>
          <l> karuṅkā laṉṟiṟ kāmar kaṭuñcūl</l>
          <l> vayavuppeṭai yakavum pāṉāṭ kaṅkuṉ</l>
          <l> maṉṟam pōḻu miṉamaṇi neṭuntēr</l>
          <l> vārā tāyiṉum varuvatu pōlac</l>
          <l> cevimuta licaikku maravamoṭu</l>
          <l> tuyiṟuṟan taṉavā ṟōḻiyeṉ kaṇṇē.</l>
        </lg>

        <lg xml:lang="en">
          <l>My eyes, they have indeed given up sleep, friend,</l>
          <l rend="indent">with the note ringing in the ear</l>
          <l rend="indent2">as if it came, even when it doesn't come,</l>
          <l rend="indent2">the long chariot with various bells, <note place="foot"> <term xml:lang="ta">iṉamaṇi </term>, just like <term xml:lang="ta"> iṉamīṉ </term>, is a formulaic compound (cf. NA 19.6, 163.4, 187.4, AN 80.10) where one feels entitled to ask whether word order makes any difference to meaning, that is, whether <term xml:lang="ta"> iṉamaṇi </term> is in any way different from <term xml:lang="ta"> maṇiyiṉam </term>. Tradition does not seem unanimous regarding that matter. While Cām. here simply  <term xml:lang="ta"> tokutiyākiya maṇi </term>-, "bells that are numerous", T.V.G. usually explains it to mean "various bells", i.e. various sorts and sizes of bells (as presumably attached to different parts of the harness), just as iṉamīṉ would mean, according to him, different sorts of fish (cf. note on KT 9.5). </note></l>
          <l rend="indent8">crossing the village common</l>
          <l rend="indent">deep at night, when the she-bird <note place="foot"> Regarding word order, one would expect <term xml:lang="ta"> peṭai </term> to be direct object here, because otherwise with <term xml:lang="ta"> aṉṟil </term> we have an unmarked direct object preceding its subject, but with respect to contents the calling female alone makes sense (she, not he, is bound to the nest by "pregnancy"), and emotionally she of course represents the longing woman. </note> with pregnancy pangs calls,</l>
          <l rend="indent2">heavily pregnant, desiring the black-legged Aṉṟil bird,</l>
          <l rend="indent3">in the nest of small stalks made from the rich stems</l>
          <l rend="indent3">of the broad-based Palmyra palm,</l>
          <l rend="indent8">trunk [like] the base of a drum. <note place="foot"> Syntax and intention of line 1 are not wholly clear, but it seems best to take the first half as an unmarked comparison for the base of the tree (which is quite rare in the KT).  </note> </l>


        </lg>
      </div>
    </body>
  </text>
